VALUES
(42, 9, 8, 42, 9, 19, 19, NULL, 'Connection of Prophetic Figures', 'Both passages emphasize the belief that significant prophetic figures, such as Elias and old prophets, have returned. This connection highlights the public perception of Jesus'' identity as linked to these revered figures.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 8, 43, 1, 21, 21, 'Elias had appeared', 'Elijah''s Prophetic Identity', 'Both passages emphasize the figure of Elias (Elijah) and the confusion surrounding his identity. In Luke, some believe Elias has appeared, while in John, John the Baptist is directly questioned about being Elias.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 8, 40, 17, 10, 10, 'Elias', 'Connection of Elias in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the figure of Elias, indicating a shared theme of prophetic expectation. The disciples'' question in Matthew reflects the speculation about Elias''s return mentioned in Luke.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 8, 41, 6, 15, 15, 'that Elias had appeared', 'Elijah and Prophets Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the belief that Jesus was associated with Elijah or a prophet. This connection highlights the public perception of Jesus as a prophetic figure, linking him to the revered prophets of the past.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 8, 41, 8, 28, 28, NULL, 'Connection of Prophetic Figures', 'Both passages emphasize the appearance of prophetic figures, specifically mentioning Elias and other prophets. This connection highlights the public perception of Jesus as a prophetic figure linked to the past.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 9, 42, 23, 8, 8, 'desired to see him', 'Herod''s Desire to See Jesus', 'This connection highlights Herod''s curiosity about Jesus in both passages. In Luke 9:9, Herod expresses a desire to see Jesus after hearing about him, which is echoed in Luke 23:8, where he is exceeding glad to finally see him.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 9, 42, 13, 31, 32, 'who is this, of whom I hear', 'Herod''s Concern for Jesus', 'This connection highlights Herod''s ongoing concern about Jesus'' identity and influence. In both passages, Herod expresses a desire to understand who Jesus is, reflecting his anxiety about the implications of Jesus'' miracles and teachings.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 10, 40, 11, 21, 21, 'desert place belonging to the city called Bethsaida', 'Connection Between Bethsaida References', 'Both passages emphasize Bethsaida, highlighting its significance in Jesus'' ministry. Luke mentions Jesus taking the apostles to a desert place belonging to Bethsaida, while Matthew pronounces woe upon the city for its unrepentance despite witnessing mighty works.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 10, 40, 14, 13, 21, 'desert place', 'Desert Place Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the setting of a ''desert place'' where Jesus and his disciples retreat. This shared location serves as a backdrop for the miraculous feeding of the multitude, highlighting the theme of provision in a desolate environment.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 10, 58, 13, 17, 17, 'took them, and went aside', 'Leadership and Accountability', 'This connection highlights the theme of leadership and the responsibility of those in authority. In Luke, the apostles return to Jesus, who takes them aside, indicating a guiding relationship, while Hebrews emphasizes the importance of obeying leaders who watch over souls.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 10, 38, 1, 10, 10, 'went aside privately into a desert place', 'Desert Place and Earthly Mission', 'This connection highlights the theme of being sent to specific locations for a purpose. In Luke, the apostles return from their mission and go to a desert place, while in Zechariah, the sent ones walk to and fro through the earth.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 10, 41, 2, 7, 7, NULL, 'Connection of Authority and Forgiveness', 'This connection highlights the authority of Jesus in both passages. In Luke, the apostles return to Jesus, indicating his role as a leader, while in Mark, the question of who can forgive sins points to divine authority, which Jesus embodies.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 10, 41, 6, 30, 45, 'desert place', 'Desert Place and Rest', 'Both passages emphasize the need for the apostles to rest in a desert place after their ministry. They highlight the transition from their work to a time of retreat with Jesus, indicating the importance of rest amidst their labor.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 10, 42, 9, 10, 17, 'desert place belonging to the city called Bethsaida', 'Feeding the Multitude Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the apostles'' return and their subsequent actions in a desert place. The transition from the apostles recounting their deeds to the miracle of feeding the multitude illustrates the continuation of Jesus'' ministry and the provision for the people.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 11, 23, 61, 1, 1, 'healed them that had need of healing', 'Healing and Proclamation Connection', 'Both passages emphasize healing and proclaiming good news. Luke mentions healing those in need, while Isaiah speaks of binding up the brokenhearted and preaching good tidings.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 11, 40, 14, 14, 14, 'healed them that had need of healing', 'Compassion and Healing Connection', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' compassion for the crowds and his healing of those in need. The mention of healing in both verses highlights a thematic parallel in Jesus'' ministry.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 11, 40, 21, 31, 31, 'kingdom of God', 'Kingdom of God Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of the kingdom of God. In Luke, Jesus speaks of the kingdom and heals those in need, while in Matthew, he highlights who enters the kingdom, contrasting the publicans and harlots with the religious leaders.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 11, 41, 6, 33, 34, 'spake unto them of the kingdom of God', 'Compassion and Teaching', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' compassion for the people and his role as a teacher. In Luke, he speaks of the kingdom of God and heals those in need, while in Mark, he teaches the crowd, moved by their need for guidance. This connection highlights the consistent theme of Jesus'' care and instruction.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 11, 42, 1, 53, 53, 'healed them that had need of healing', 'Connection of Provision and Healing', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of providing for those in need. In Luke 9:11, Jesus heals those who need healing, while Luke 1:53 speaks of filling the hungry with good things, highlighting a divine concern for the marginalized.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 11, 42, 5, 31, 31, 'healed them that had need of healing', 'Healing and Need for Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the need for healing, with Luke 9:11 highlighting Jesus healing those in need and Luke 5:31 stating that the sick need a physician. This connection highlights the theme of Jesus as a healer for those who recognize their need.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 11, 43, 4, 34, 34, 'the kingdom of God', 'Connection of Purpose and Action', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of doing God''s will. In Luke, Jesus actively heals and teaches about the kingdom, while in John, he expresses that fulfilling God''s work is his primary purpose.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 12, 28, 13, 5, 5, 'desert place', 'Wilderness and Provision Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the wilderness experience, highlighting the need for sustenance in desolate places. Luke 9:12 mentions a ''desert place,'' while Hosea 13:5 refers to the ''wilderness'' and ''great drought.''', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 12, 40, 15, 23, 23, NULL, 'Disciples'' Requests for Dismissal', 'This connection highlights the disciples'' role in both passages as they seek to send away those in need. In Luke, they request to send the multitude away, while in Matthew, they ask Jesus to send away a woman seeking help.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 12, 41, 6, 35, 44, 'in a desert place', 'Feeding the Multitude Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the disciples'' concern about the crowd''s need for food in a desert place. They both highlight the urgency of sending the multitude away to find sustenance, leading to the miraculous feeding of the five thousand.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 12, 43, 6, 1, 1, 'desert place', 'Desert Place and Sea of Galilee', 'This connection highlights the geographical movement of Jesus and his disciples. Both passages emphasize the transition from a desert place to the sea, indicating a shift in setting and context for Jesus'' ministry.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 12, 19, 78, 19, 20, 'in a desert place', 'Provision in the Wilderness', 'Both passages emphasize the challenge of providing sustenance in a desert setting. In Luke, the disciples express concern about feeding the multitude in a desert place, while in Psalms, the people question God''s ability to provide food in the wilderness.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 12, 26, 34, 25, 25, 'desert place', 'Safety in Wilderness', 'This connection highlights the theme of safety and provision in wilderness settings. Both passages emphasize the idea of dwelling safely in a desert or wilderness place, suggesting a divine care for those in need.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 12, 40, 14, 15, 21, NULL, 'Feeding the Multitude Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the disciples'' concern for the crowd''s need for food in a desert place. They express the urgency to send the multitude away, which leads to Jesus'' miraculous provision of food.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 13, 20, 11, 24, 25, 'Give ye them to eat', 'Generosity and Provision', 'This connection highlights the theme of generosity leading to abundance. In both passages, the act of giving, whether food or resources, is linked to increased provision and blessings.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 13, 12, 4, 42, 43, 'Give ye them to eat', 'Miraculous Provision of Food', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of miraculous provision of food for a large group. In each instance, a limited amount of food is presented, yet it is sufficient to feed many, highlighting God''s ability to provide abundantly from little.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
